services.description: [Focus: FPS] Core Remote Desktop service. On systems that never host RDP sessions, can be disabled to trim listeners and session management overhead.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.description: [Focus: FPS] Configures Remote Desktop and terminal services. Safe to disable on gaming rigs that never use RDP in or out.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.displayName: Remote Desktop Services UserMode Port Redirector
services.description: [Focus: FPS] Handles peripheral redirection for Remote Desktop. Can be disabled if Remote Desktop is never used.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.description: [Focus: FPS] Wireless configuration helper for easy router/device pairing. On wired or already-configured Wi-Fi setups it can be disabled for gaming sessions.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.description: [Focus: FPS] Manages portable device detection and auto-sync. If you are not syncing phones/cameras while gaming, it can be disabled.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.description: [Focus: FPS] Monitors activity for parental controls. Unneeded on a single-user gaming account and can be fully disabled.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.description: [Focus: FPS] Core smart card service. If you never authenticate with smart cards, you can disable it to reduce background security polling.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.description: [Focus: FPS] Central event logging service. Disabling entirely can break troubleshooting and some features; only adjust via Custom matrix if you fully understand the risks.
services.notes: Added from extended service research for Falcon Process Lab.

services.description: [Focus: FPS, Latency] Core antivirus engine for Microsoft Defender. Disabling can slightly reduce background CPU/disk usage but removes real‑time AV protection.
services.notes: Only consider on an offline or highly controlled gaming machine with a separate security plan. Disabling this stops Defender's core scanning engine.

services.description: Tracks and reports security health to the Windows Security app. Disabling hides or breaks parts of the Windows Security dashboard.
services.notes: Danger tweak. It may cause the Windows Security / Defender app to show errors or stop opening correctly.

services.description: Monitors antivirus, firewall, and other security providers and shows notifications.
services.notes: Disabling can stop security notifications and may make the Windows Security interface unreliable.

services.description: Configures and manages Wi‑Fi connections. Disabling will typically break Wi‑Fi connectivity.
services.notes: Only consider on a desktop permanently wired by Ethernet with Wi‑Fi fully unused.

services.description: Obtains IP configuration from DHCP servers. Disabling often breaks network connectivity unless you manually configure static IPs.
services.notes: Danger tweak. Only advanced users with static IP setups should ever experiment with this.

services.description: Caches DNS results and assists with name resolution. Disabling can break or slow domain name lookups.
services.notes: Generally leave this on. It's exposed in Custom only for advanced experiments; disabling can break Internet access on many setups.

services.description: [Focus: Latency] Disables the Themes service to remove theme overhead. Purely lab/benchmark use – desktop visuals will look basic.
services.notes: Only use in a dedicated lab or benchmark account. Visual styles revert toward classic/basic; not recommended for daily use.

services.description: [Focus: FPS] Handles AutoPlay notifications and some shell-level reactions to media insertion (USB sticks, optical media).
services.notes: Turning this off removes AutoPlay prompts and shell popups when drives/media are attached. It is generally safe on desktop gaming rigs and can reduce small UI event noise.

services.description: [Focus: Process Count] Disables NFC / payments secure element helpers.
services.notes: Safe for desktop rigs with no NFC/payment usage.

services.description: [Focus: Latency] Stops Xbox Live authentication background service.
services.notes: Safe when not using Microsoft Store / Xbox titles on that account.

services.description: [Focus: Process Count] Disables XPS print pipeline helpers.
services.notes: Safe if you never use XPS printing.
